image.altText: a couple stands under an umbrella overlooking the sydney harbour bridge as strom clouds brew

props.synopsis: Four people are in hospital in a serious and stable condition after they were struck by lightning outside Sydney's Botanic Gardens, as firefighters and SES respond to numerous incidents as a result of the storm.

title.children: Four people hit by lightning, houses set alight, flood rescues as powerful storm sweeps across Sydney

image.altText: Premier Chris Minns in a blazer and blue tie

props.synopsis: After "leaning on" alcohol during COVID, Mr Minns decided to try to stop drinking for a month. He soon discovered not drinking led to "massive positive change" in his life.

title.children: NSW Premier Chris Minns hasn't had a drink for two years. He says it's been 'life-changing'

image.altText: A woman and man with their arms around each other.

props.synopsis: Evgenia Kara-Murza, the wife of jailed Russian opposition politician Vladimir Kara-Murza, has no doubts who was responsible for the death of Alexei Navalny.

title.children: 'His life is in danger': Now Navalny is dead, Putin's other imprisoned rivals could be next

image.altText: Photorealistic concept art of a warship gliding through open seas.

props.synopsis: Labor reveals the cost of the massive Hunter-class frigate project has leapt from $45 billion to almost $65 billion, as it prepares to trim the program while unveiling other shipbuilding plans.

title.children: $20 billion funding ‘hole’ in troubled Hunter warships, Labor claims

image.altText: A young woman with long blonde hair and wearing a sparkly silver bodysuit blows a kiss.

props.synopsis: "It's a love story, baby just say yes." They're some of the lyrics to one of Taylor Swift's most famous songs and in Australia her fans are paying back the love in the most wholesome ways.

title.children: Why the feeling of belonging is just as important as Taylor Swift's music

image.altText: taylor swift performs in melbourne

props.synopsis: Fans brace storms to catch a glimpse of global superstar Taylor Swift, as her private jet lands at Sydney Airport.

title.children: Swiftmania hits Sydney as superstar arrives in the Harbour City

image.altText: An American Staffordshire Terrier sits in a grass field

props.synopsis: An inquest is considering whether a NSW Central Coast council could have removed a family dog, which fatally mauled a 5-week-old baby, after it killed another dog a month earlier.

title.children: Inquest considers whether council could have seized family dog before it killed baby

image.altText: A crowd of young women and girls pack in extremely tightly to a doorway, some reaching out their hands.

props.synopsis: Israel is continuing to telegraph a ground offensive in Rafah, where more than half of Gaza's 2.3 million Palestinians have sought refuge since the beginning of the conflict.

title.children: Israel vows to 'finish the job' in Gaza as war cabinet member threatens Ramadan deadline for Rafah

image.altText: Christopher Walker arrives at court wearing sunglasses

props.synopsis: Twenty-one-year-old Christopher Walker has been spared jail time after stealing a car and crashing it into traffic on the Sydney Harbour Bridge while on drugs.

title.children: Driver of stolen car in fiery Sydney Harbour Bridge crash escapes jail time

image.altText: Power plant with power lines in foreground

props.synopsis: EnergyAustralia says meeting its green hydrogen target for a new gas power plant in NSW is becoming more challenging.

title.children: Green hydrogen supply chain 'not there yet' as $300 million coal alternative starts pumping out power

image.altText: the outside of a building

props.synopsis: The state's casino commission said it was not satisfied Star Casino had done enough to address its failings following the first inquiry.

title.children: Sydney's Star Casino will face second inquiry less than two years after damning report

image.altText: Woman and dog wrapped in muslin cloth

props.synopsis: Struggling to pay rent in Sydney, Alys McDonough bought what she says was one of the cheapest houses in Australia. She's now back living there, with no mains power and with a bit of ceiling missing, but she says she's sorted.

title.children: Struggling to pay rent, Alys bought a dilapidated house in the outback for about $12,000

image.altText: A sign of a waste facility with an arrow pointing towards public trailer waste.

props.synopsis: A man accused of fatally bashing his "frail" housemate and then putting his body in a wheelie bin that was later discovered at an Adelaide dump has been found guilty of murder.

title.children: Man guilty of murdering housemate whose body was found in bin at Adelaide dump

image.altText: Peter Dutton at a press conference at EastCoast Beverages at Kulnura on NSW Central Coast.

props.synopsis: Opposition Leader Peter Dutton has seized on the recent arrival to warn an "armada" is on its way and has accused the government of weakening Operation Sovereign Borders. But has it?

title.children: How does Australia's boat turnbacks policy work, and has it changed?

image.altText: A wooden cross sticks up out of green grass, against a blue sky

props.synopsis: Dozens of people have been killed in a clash between tribes in Papua New Guinea's Highlands that's been described as an "ambush".

title.children: At least 49 people have been killed in the largest PNG Highlands 'massacre' in recent history. Here's what we know

image.altText: Two men captured on CCTV loading allegedly stolen property into a car boot.

props.synopsis: District Court hears James and Gregory Brockman were in the midst of a nine-day methamphetamine binge when they tied up the man, threatened him with a shotgun and stole more than $30,000 of his possessions.

title.children: Kalgoorlie brothers jailed for nine years after holding 69yo man at gunpoint during home invasion

image.altText: A group of people all loaded up into the back of a small truck with no back door.

props.synopsis: Fighting, fuel shortages and Israeli raids have put the Nasser Hospital in the southern city of Khan Younis out of service, health officials say.

title.children: Patients forced to evacuate Gaza's second-largest hospital, local and United Nations health officials say

image.altText: A man dressed in police uniform and holding a gun stands on a street with cars nearby.

props.synopsis: Papua New Guinea Prime Minister James Marape urges tribal warriors to "allow disputes to be resolved" after a massacre in the highlands province of Enga killed dozens.

title.children: PNG prime minister urges tribes to 'lay down your arms' after deadly massacre

image.altText: The Prime Minister stands in a leafy green area holding a press conference

props.synopsis: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese says Operation Sovereign Borders is working as intended and the arrival of a boat carrying asylum seekers on WA's shore is "unfortunate" but not a policy failure.

title.children: Albanese says asylum seeker boat arrival 'unfortunate' but rubbishes claims government to blame

image.altText: Composite of a man wearing an orange mankini while on a horse

props.synopsis: Mr Rose has been cleared by Equestrian Australia of any wrong-doing and is hopeful he can get on with preparation for the Paris Olympics.

title.children: 'A bit of fun': Olympic showjumping champion Shane Rose shocked after being stood down for wearing a mankini

image.altText: A black coloured tractor in the Antarctic snow with whispy clouds across the blue sky. A large halo surrounds the sun.

props.synopsis: Researchers from the Australian Antarctic Division have completed one of the most ambitious expeditions since the 1960s, but the world's ice remains locked deep in the frozen continent.

title.children: 'So many ways you can be tripped up in Antarctica': Polar research delayed after COVID strikes

image.altText: A person wheels their trolley past the end of a supermarket aisle. They are blurred from the motion and are not identifiable.

props.synopsis: Leaked emails reveal for the first time the tactics Coles employs when a supplier seeks a price increase and how it has taken advantage of inflation to boost profits.

title.children: You've been paying more at the checkout: Four Corners reveals the tactics used by Coles and Woolworths

image.altText: Two sisters hug and smile for the camera.

props.synopsis: A girl seriously injured in a car crash that resulted in the death of her sister in a family road trip to a Taylor Swift concert is in a critical but stable condition, her godmother says.

title.children: 'In the best place possible': Bedside vigil for girl critically injured in crash that killed sister on Taylor Swift trip

image.altText: White rocket sits in hangar with Australian flag in background.

props.synopsis: A Queensland-built rocket will strive to reach orbit from the northern town of Bowen in what company bosses say is the first locally made craft to lift-off from Australian soil.

title.children: First glimpse of historic rocket set to launch Australia into the space age

image.altText: Woman's face.

props.synopsis: A new coronial inquest has been scheduled into the disappearance of the young Sydney woman who failed to meet her mother at Newcastle Railway Station in 1994.

title.children: Thirty years on, answers sought over fate of missing model Revelle Balmain

image.altText: ian wilkinson

props.synopsis: Pastor Ian Wilkinson has delivered a sermon to his church for the first time speaking publicly since his world was turned upside down.

title.children: Mushroom meal survivor breaks his silence six months since his wife died from mushroom poisoning

image.altText: Two women seated on couch with toddler girl. The hands of a photographer are blurred in foreground

props.synopsis: After the Matildas’ World Cup glory, star midfielder Katrina Gorry introduces us to the tiny secret weapon who rekindled her love for the game.

title.children: At the top of her game but battling to get out of bed, Katrina Gorry reveals how she overcame her 'dark place'

image.altText: Inside a factory where steel is being made.

props.synopsis: The steelmaker continues to work on its "decarbonisation journey" while revealing plans to diversify the use of 1,200 hectares of land it owns in New South Wales, Victoria and New Zealand.

title.children: BlueScope posts steady profit result while positioning for ongoing carbon transition challenges

image.altText: Fence with a danger asbestos sign at the Rozelle Parklands as the clean up continues

props.synopsis: The NSW Environment Protection Agency said that 41 sites have been identified as having bonded asbestos, with 683 tests returning negative results since last month.

title.children: Another school, supermarket among new sites identified as Sydney asbestos debacle grows

image.altText: A truck of cattle is parked next to a large boat, ready to loaded for export

props.synopsis: Indonesia has finally issued import permits for Australian cattle, with the first ship now on the water bound for Jakarta.

title.children: Cattle sail from Darwin as Indonesian live export trade resumes

image.altText: A close up on a woman looking seriously at the camera. She is older, and looks sad. The background is black.

props.synopsis: A crisis inside one of northern Australia's most important legal entities has led to a severe shortage of lawyers in Alice Springs, leaving some of Australia's most vulnerable residents to represent themselves in court.

title.children: 'National disgrace': Verna's son has been locked up for two months and hasn't been able to access a lawyer

image.altText: A retro motel in the 50's, large American styles signage decorates the front and an old car is parked out the front

props.synopsis: Across Australia many motel restaurants once a hive of activity 50 years ago are being used as storage, conference rooms, or common rooms. But what changed?

title.children: What ever happened to the golden age of motel dining?
